Specifically, the third objective of â€œComparing Modeling Approachesâ€ù is related to the trade-offs of interpretable and black-box predictive models. Q11: I miss my work in international development and on truly difficult social science problems. I enjoy problem-solving and am always eager to help where I can. These large-scale challenges are a great way to stay involved and help a collective group of people advance science and understanding of difficult, fluid problems facing the world today.

Professionally and in general, I am very interested in applying machine learning techniques to social science problems in such a way that provides new insights. In particular, we plan to apply a novel algorithm Correlation Explanation (CorEx) to the Fragile Families data set. CorEx has already been to shown to find new and informative latent factors in other applied contexts, such as in cancer treatment (https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2016/11/11/how-a-researcher-used-her-computational-know-how-to-beat-her-own-ovarian-cancer/), and we are excited to have the chance to apply the algorithm to such an important social science problem with longstanding consequences.Personally, I have spent the overwhelming majority of my life growing up in a single-mother household. While I have been fortunate enough to have my father in my life, I still understand the ongoing stress and issues that come from growing up under divorced parents. I am particularly invested in helping make progress on this project as to help children from fragile families that have not had as many lucky opportunities as I have.

I am particularly interested in exploring how machine learning methods can be applied to this problem and how they compare to traditional approaches in the social science. I'd like to use this challenge as an opportunity to learn more about the Fragile Families dataset, to better see how machine learning can complement more traditional social scientific analyses, and as a way to learn some new methods.

I want to understand issues of transparency and accountability when it comes to making inferences on data which is socially relevant and where incorrect inferences can have an impact on people's lives. I am interested in understanding if algorithms in these situations can be gamed, and if black-box machine learning behaves in an interpretable and robust manner.
